Brooks -

As you&#39;ve discovered, a copy operation in Matlab of a Cantera object is  
a &#39;shallow&#39; copy operation, because the Matlab object really just holds  
a pointer. The same is true in Python.
The easiest way to create two independent versions of any Cantera  
object is to construct each one independently, for example:

g = air;
h = air;

This seems to me to be just about as easy as writing &#39;h = g,&#39; so I  
wonder if implementing a &#39;deep&#39; copy operation is really worth it.  
Comments, anyone?

Dave G.



On Monday, August 18, 2003, at 05:16 PM, brooksmoses1 wrote:

&gt; So, supposing I want to create two gas mixtures in Matlab, with
&gt; initially identical properties.  The naive way to do this is as
&gt; follows:
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; g = air;
&gt;&gt;&gt; h = g;
&gt;
&gt; Now, this doesn&#39;t actually work, as the following shows:
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; temperature(g)
&gt;    300
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; set(h,&#39;T&#39;,600);
&gt;&gt;&gt; temperature(h)
&gt;    600
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; temperature(g)
&gt;    600
&gt;
&gt; What&#39;s happening, as I understand it, is that h and g are stored as
&gt; pointers, and so &quot;h = g&quot; means creating a new pointer h that points
&gt; to the same mixture as g.  And so there still is only one gas mixture
&gt; extant.  Is this understanding correct?
&gt;
&gt; And the real question -- is there a built-in way of creating an h
&gt; that is in fact a _separate_ copy of g?  Or do I have to do this
&gt; manually, by defining a &quot;copy_mixture&quot; function from scratch that
&gt; creates a &quot;blank&quot; h and then sets all the fractions and variables to
&gt; equal those of g?  I looked through the Solution methods, and didn&#39;t
&gt; see anything that appeared to be an obvious answer.
&gt;
&gt; If such a built-in function doesn&#39;t currently exist in Cantera, I&#39;d
&gt; like to request it as a feature on future releases.
&gt;
